s; Pat Jackson, Robert Hamer and Joseph Losey, and even of a maverick critic Raymond Durgnat. Features personal insights from those inidividually implicated in 1950s cinema; Corin Redgrave on Michael Redgrave, Isabel Quigly on film reviewing, and Bryony Dixon of the BFI on archiving and preservation. Presents a provocative challenge to conventional wisdom about 1950s film and rediscovers the Festival of Britain decade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1950s British cinema.  aBritish film culture.  aBritish film history.  aFestival of Britain.  aJack Hawkins.  aJoseph Losey.  aLindsay Anderson.  aMichael Redgrave.  aPat Jackson.  aRaymond Durgnat.  aRobert Hamer.  aWhite Corridors.  aart cinema aesthetics.  aauteurism.  afilm reviewing.  amaverick directors.  apost-Ealing films.  awar films.1 aAldgate, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Bryony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEasen, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiddings, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedling, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInglis, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKidd, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacey, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4